toddycat: keep calm and check logs
add_recommand: the toddycat advanced persistent threat (apt) group has been actively conducting sophisticated cyber espionage operations since december 2020, targeting high-profile entities across europe and asia. initially focusing on compromising publicly exposed servers using vulnerabilities in microsoft exchange and distributing malware such as the ninja trojan and samurai backdoor, toddycat has evolved its toolset over time. recent investigations have uncovered a new set of loaders used to deploy the ninja trojan as a second stage, along with tailored loaders for long-term persistence. additionally, the group employs a variety of tools such as lofise for file collection, dropbox and onedrive uploaders for exfiltration, and passive udp backdoors for remote command execution. post-exploitation activities involve lateral movement, discovery of domain accounts and servers, and targeted file collection using scripts. the collected data is compressed and exfiltrated using public file storage services.
